It is at least clear in Germany that we have the village as a subdivision of the ‘pagus' and that it regulated in some way the occupatiori of the land compriscd in it ⁶. The chief description that we have might in most points approach to a description of a free village under the ‘llfarlt’ system ⁶. Yet it would be bold to say that permanent individual possession of land finds no place in the statement l, or that there might not have been cases ln which the whole village was a cluster of dependente ona common lord⁸, or that other intermediate forms 0f tenure may not have been in existence. Great movements, such as those which launched the Teutonic tribes against the decaying Roman empire, would lead naturally to great changes in these matters ⁹, and it is more remarkable that so much of the account given in this treatise should be recognizable than that so much should have passed away.
